The two-way matchup: MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We'll help you choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can be used to make a phone call.
It makes it clear that it's better to just buy a phone.
Still, there are many reasons why you should buy a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
You're probably having a hard time getting a top-quality, expensive record player home to listen to that latest Maxim Turbulenc album.
On the one hand, these musical products do not appear on the bakelite plates, but there is no objective reason for this in terms of quality.
But if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz, or blues records, you're probably dreaming of playing one.
It's similar to travel, which is compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are price and quality categories here too.
Some people may find it unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it hard to accept a $20 marketplace headset.
Two extremes where there's plenty of room for everyone.
There's a wide range.
The life of the elements is also important.
Some high-quality music players are capable of more than just playing music, but also of what most mobile phones do not by chance.
No device today is as universal as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a miracle, because no refrigerator can barbecue and no television can take pictures.
Multi-functional phones have their drawbacks.
The more features you use on your phone, the more times the display sends to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy consumers.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than 10 or 12 hours, usually much less.
In this respect, musical players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap phones, you can expect them to be out of your game for a few hours.
If you even use a mobile phone, get another charger for your workplace for safety reasons - this applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players won't have that problem, even the worst ones can handle at least nine hours of continuous operation with one charge.
The next problem is when you upload music to your mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector and not all of them can be connected directly to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but few card readers can handle miniature memory cards without an adapter.
With a few exceptions, the iPod does not need any special software.
You just need to load the device from the computer to the music via USB.
Most mobile phones and players already have their own library of music sorted by the artist, album, genre name or user rating.
Some devices only display a structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating systems).
Players are easier to handle, mobile phones know more
When choosing a particular device, you should be interested in the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, the convenience of handling.
If you are primarily listening to music in the background and only listen to it for a short time each day, such as on a tram, any MP3 player is a good fit.
And that's what any mobile phone can do.
You don't have to pay much attention to what music formats your mobile or player can play.
MP3 is a problem for everyone, and the vast majority of the music you get will be in this format.
MP3 is among the most widely used and, in addition, the vast majority of devices also deal with WMA-style music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the relevant pages of the service provider (or other service provider) via the mobile internet and to purchase the song or album.
This service itself can be a compelling argument for acquiring a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the providers' offerings are shallow and generally limited to one-hour radio broadcasts.
The prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this is the way music is sold (whether on GSM, the Internet or wireless) that will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever he feels like listening to something, he's poking his cell phone in his pocket while his forgotten MP3 player is at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry earphones or at least speakers.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only a few MP3 players.
For many, the most likely benefit of music phones is the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 crowns.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get quite a decent walkman.
But most of the time, you're limited by the lack of a conventional earpiece.
The best and most technically equipped phones with traditional 3,5 mm diameter hole headphones can cost up to 15,000 kroner.
The advantage of players is, however, among other things, their ease of handling.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest - players (see our selection) are really all people's problems.
Minimal function, handling similar to the previously common tape recorder or phonograph is obvious.
There is no risk of a crash in the accidental mobile internet form, or the subsequent massive bill for data transmission.
What device to choose
The most affordable mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have access to interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, etc.).
If you add the appropriate card, you'll be able to get up to 2,000 crowns.
But be careful.
The basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB or more.
Only the most expensive can figure out what to do with up to 8GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and you want to buy even a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowont, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Irver.
On the basis of capacity (maximum 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 kr.
If you're in a more demanding audience, choose a special mobile walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have separate MP3 control buttons, which makes the handling convenient to approach the MP3 player.
The industry was led by Sony Ericsson, which has walker-series phones with the same user interface as its MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands can provide the same service in the same price category up to 4000 kr, but with a higher memory capacity (about 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I should.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Yet something is missing here - a virtual service provider that forces classic providers to cut substantial prices.
Maybe it won't be like this for long.
We have written on the A.Mobil.cz website many times that Czech providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the CTU, which pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
The latest move by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges may therefore lead to a potential conflict - some Czech mobile phone service customers will find text messages from abroad cheaper than their home customers.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
That might sound contradictory, given that we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed with Pavel Dvořák, the chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Office Council, who has stated several times before that there is no place for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the classic provider with its own network is likely to have little chance of getting it (although it is likely to be difficult to find frequencies).
But there's another option, the virtual service provider.
It was the move of virtual providers to the mobile market that brought about a significant price decline, which was followed by the classic services.
Even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile came to market in the UK, we heard sounds like ours.
However, it has been shown that such providers have a place and can be truly successful.
Yet, we do not need to go too far for example.
In February this year, we informed you of the launch of Mobilking in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider has managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
In the meantime, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that they can focus on a much smaller target group.
It requires far fewer customers than a traditional service provider to operate efficiently.
It does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus tend to be low-cost - offering cheap calls and text messages, but often being offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least 50 percent cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a target group can be a good bet.
This service is specifically targeted at men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - who they like, who they can trust", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual service.
It is difficult to say whether we can adopt a view similar to that of Poland.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone spokesman, doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small compared to the segmental approach on which most virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied with the services it provides.'
In the Czech Republic, the mobile phone providers claim that there is no chance
However, it seems almost certain that if there is any virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about a successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem very hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking is more likely to take place in other countries in our region", Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
It has indirectly demonstrated that the existing mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not overly sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they do their best to avoid any potential competition.
The GTS Novera Group has long been keen to launch the virtual service provider, thus taking a further step towards making Telefonica O2 a true competitor in the corporate customer market.
"We are very interested in providing our customers with not only wired but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner the better.
We have discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile providers.
Some of them have already made progress in negotiations", says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
From unofficial information, it seems we might be lucky enough to have the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
But his birth is surrounded by a wall of impenetrable silence.
"At the moment we do not think that a full-fledged virtual provider has a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market is very special unlike other markets.
We have not been so far impressed by a diverse subject offering a complex and serious project in this area", Vlastimil Sršeň, press officer at Telefónica 02 told Mobil.cz.
The other providers also refer to the specific situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokeswoman for T-Mobile, exceptionally agrees with O2 and adds: "We have not yet recorded a single viable and bilaterally beneficial business project on which to build further".
And he added, "It's unlikely that any virtual service provider will be available on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we should have a concrete agreement on the table to think in such a short-term way".
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
From a customer's perspective, that's what we consider the most affordable.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to partner to build shared networks for fast mobile internet.'
Responsible offices - on a leash with service providers
The mobile service providers' behaviour is easy to understand, and the entry of a new service provider would increase competition, lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in profits.
So why facilitate entry into such a competition?
When the service providers are able to cooperate on something important, the U:fon's roots are also evident.
The biggest pressure on ČTÚ was probably put on the birth of T-Mobile's U:phone.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the CTU website.
But right now, U:fon is coming up as a good argument for why we shouldn't allow the virtual service provider access.
Martina Kemrová added: 'The mobile market competition environment has recently been marked by the entry of the fourth mobile provider into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of a new player into the market and its services imposes high demands.'
However, given the mobile phone providers' attitude, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulators is quite surprising.
However, it is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately, unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition.
The Competition Authority shall be the only authority to do so.
But the Bureau is characterized by its attitude to the whole problem.
'The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible if the contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure had been concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional providers,' stated Kristián Chlapua, of the Department of Foreign Relations at the Economic Competition Office, in response to our question.
A statement so worded by the representatives of the providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, it is more than strange that the Office should represent the interests of consumers and, inter alia, ensure that no one is able to recover from their market situation.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a country where virtual providers generally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the decline in the price of mobile services".
However, it is likely that the interest of ÚOHS does not include the correct functioning of the market environment and the pressure to reduce prices.
In this case, the very tangible consistency of the three mobile service providers' responses is truly shocking.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence is almost self-evident.
As with gas stations, the exact same gas prices are probably just a coincidence and a hard-fought competition.
'The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither provider has a leading position, i.e. no proportionate responsibility for its market activities.
The telecoms regulator is likely to lack the tools needed to open up the mobile market of virtual providers", Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership is one of the many points of discussion.
There is of course an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, which shows that telecommunications is the only market in terms of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech provider is in a leading position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the approval of the network operator is always required for the existence of a virtual service provider.
And the mobile provider, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So in a certain segment, it's necessarily dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, there should be minimal evidence for UOHS that three mobile carriers behave in a markedly similar manner.
Meanwhile, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in the course of negotiations with all the providers.
The assignment of responsibility to ČTÚ is a relatively common tactic in telecommunications whereby the ÚOHS takes its hand off the whole case.
We've met this guy in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Telecommunications Law did not allow the extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
This is something that the representatives of the UOHS should know well, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one's watching.
In the meantime, some virtual service providers, many of which are already operating on Czech mobile networks, remain unaware.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service lists, but which are only partially public.
Because they're multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife, and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
These companies' listings usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic is that the company is acting against the service provider as a classic business customer who orders large quantities of SIM cards.
As a preferred customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that all Czech mobile service providers' commercial terms prohibit a similar pre-emption.
"If there were cases you mention, it would be a breach of contract that we would be dealing with and could lead to the termination of cooperation with that company", Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
But it is highly unlikely that news of such activity would not have reached the people responsible for the mobile service providers.
The three companies mentioned above may be in the first place thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no provider is defending itself against such a procedure.
These companies have a considerable profit from their activities and, unlike real virtual providers, are not particularly threatened by their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of the potential problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that their phone does not have a SIM card in their name and therefore cannot have it in full as general customers of mobile operators.'
But that's what the CTU should be strangely about.
In addition, another question arises for the UOHS.
If mobile providers are blind to a similar process, why are they preventing the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has a relatively strong right to disclose such activity and, if it does not wish to, should not be satisfied with the explanation from the service providers that they did not suspect any such activity and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a marked decline in the prices of services.
In the meantime, virtually in all countries where virtual providers have been established, traditional providers have been trying to prevent them more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at this time that regulators intervened, which did not protect the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Then, through formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual service provider that others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are taking the whole case to one another.
In our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertain competencies are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be back on track.
If a service provider allows the establishment of a virtual mobile service provider, it is difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not get more expensive phone calls.
