The Prague transport company will ship on Wednesday for the first time with a chip card.
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be the date in the history of the Prague Transport Company when the first passenger to board the subway, train and buses will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The coupon can currently be obtained by about 100,000 people who have an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day and 90-day coupons and an annual coupons (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and can also save them on their chip cards at the Transport Company's information centres and destinations at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The coupons can be purchased online from yesterday via the transport company's website www.dpp.cz.
By the afternoon, the service had been used by more than 400 customers.
Those who are starting to use online commerce may eventually forget about the subway station ticket windows, where they regularly have to wait in long lines for tickets.
The voucher can be purchased online and added to the Opencard card in one of the 13 accounts of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers have a stand with trained servers to help interested people shop online and save their purchased coupons to their cards", said Martin Opatrný, a spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, electronic vouchers will also be saved to Opencard in some self-service vending machines installed in the hallways.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket holders, and passengers may have noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florence and Vltavská subway stations.
"There are five of them in the city now, but by the end of the year they should be eighty", Opatrný added.
The coupon is checked by the driver instead of the automated
The machines that start tomorrow are simple to operate.
Just put in the Opencard chip card and the prepaid coupon will go away on its own.
Electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area from tomorrow.
So the trains and bus stations around the city are 300 to 499, which are mainly used by people from Central Czech Republic to travel to the capital.
"On trains in Prague with integrated transport, the trains were fitted with card readers to determine the zone validity of coupons", explained Filip Drápal of Ropid, the organiser of the Prague public transport calendar, who checked the tickets.
On buses around town, card readers are installed at the driver's desk.
The driver must therefore not only show the chip card when boarding but also place the Opencard in a designated location on the side of the cash register.
The driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"For example, if the passenger needs to check the validity of coupons, the easiest way is to ask the driver to do so", Drápal added.
Passengers who travel on non-city buses and will not remember when their coupon expires can go back to the self-service card saving machines.
Information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the device's display.
The Swedes wanted a referendum from the United States
In 1945, the Swedish Germans demanded that Šumava be annexed to the United States.
This is revealed in the letter that is in the collection of the South Czech Science Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It is said that this was the wish of a group of Swedish Germans in 1945 to the President of the United States.
This is also shown by a letter from a private archive that is now in the collection of the South Czech Science Library.
The Germans in Česky Krumlov requested the US president not to allow the re-ceded of the "Sumavai County" to the Czech Republic, which was taken over by Hitler under the Munich Treaty.
"We have correctly interpreted the situation and we want to be sure in the words that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors or enemies, but as liberators", the letter said, signing the words "People who bear the fate of Shumava in their hearts".
Since joining Czechoslovakia would give the Sudeten Germans, despite their supposed knowledge of Czech national character, only hope for brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the US president to take over the protectorate over Šumava "now and forever".
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of four million inhabitants, it would consider this area a foreign country to us, oppressing and exaggerating the minority and contributing almost nothing to the victory of the Allies", the letter states.
The reason the authors couldn't sign is allegedly because of fear of revenge from the "Czech oppressors".
So if the president of the United States were to allegedly doubt the views of the Schumacher Germans, it would be enough for the Schumacher County to hold a referendum on whether its citizens want to become part of the United States and live under US patronage.
Although the letter's text may seem a little naive given the current knowledge of postwar history, some historians say it adequately reflects the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even if the Czech Germans had the slightest idea that they would be expelled from the country, few of them recognized the possibility.
