In the park of experiences in Greater Orlando - a few miles from everything that is glittering, loud and mighty - lies a quiet little town where the pride and complexity of African-American life was born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to integrate into the country and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as what she described in 1935: "Five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown leather, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guavas, and two school towns, without a prison".
It's a place of pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have already attended the annual Zora Festival, which is celebrated in Eatonville in honor of Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction - which is also listed in the Florida Roadmap published by the Federal Writers' Project for the Depression - is separate from its surroundings.
It was as independent, dignified, and secluded as it was in the 1930's, when, according to Hurston, black people in Florida, the city, often refused to share their true thoughts with white people, who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing".
Even in the year when black presidential candidate Barack Obama encouraged open debate on the issue of race, many here are distrustful of the outsiders' views.
"We take great care to tell our story", said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here all his life and is a member of the city's oldest church.
"You have to tell it right".
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
It's a historic model of black exposure, but it's also a community of almost 2,400 people where poverty rates are twice the national average.
Partly a literary hub, partly an example of the American slavery that has created, sometimes despised, sometimes praised, the southern, urban, black culture that thrives in the shade of the oak trees.
It is not surprising, then, that the inhabitants here are both proud and defensive.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora, (who everyone calls Hurston here).
In his books written in sincere, strong dialect - such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937) - he introduced his hometown to the world.
The Florida Road Book, paragraph five, transformed the city along Route 17, which leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in both life and literature, as well as in drumming, introduced his readers to the business of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then to the more trusted spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road is a modern public school, with a brown foundation with a white corner, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds, maintained by Howard Miller, who can barely read or write".
She mentioned Dash's new husband, and she wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything you need at temporary accommodations".
