However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, sitting in his chair, "I never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were never reprinted.
It seemed like Eatonville, along with most of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although she was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived before.
There were no major memorabilia or large public readings in Eatonville.
