"I'm not taking pictures on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal perspective". Photographer Günther Bauer
No decoration, no hair, no dancing shoes.
Flamenco masters are in the flesh, without the excitement of performing, to get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
The artist, on the one hand.
On the other hand, the average person.
And these two sides cannot be separated except in intimate moments away from the audience, when we can touch a personal movement, capture the depth of a caught eye, or marvel at the beauty of an artist's hands, empty but expressive, when they're not on stage.
In the German photograph series Günther Bauer Flamenco-people, he combines the theatrical talent of singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photos, he presents flamenco's distinctive iconography from different points of view.
The exhibition, which is part of Flamenco Photography Month, "reflects the growing international importance of flamenco day by day", the creator believes, adding that the Flamenco-people "can be played by anyone, as the images make the observer realize that these images do not typically depict artists.
These people who are being lentiled on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and capture the audience.
But stage photography is not a way to capture their personality.
Their personality and character are deep within their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to use the camera to embrace the personality of the great flamenco".
Inspired by the Cante de las Minas Festival, Bauer embarked on a long journey in 1997, taking portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a disc camera.
This portrait, thanks to the camera and the choice of subject matter, evokes classic photography.
However, the use of different stylistic tools breaks with traditional imagery and suggests modernity. The following thought faithfully reflects Bauer's view of flamenco: "It is a music with traditional roots, but one that changes day by day and is always impressive".
It's not the dance, not the song or the music itself, but rather the artist's personality, character, that enchant the audience.
The main motivation of the works that can be seen in the El Fotomata Gallery these days is the search for a meeting with the essence, the artistic magic, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and representation.
The names of well-known flamenco artists, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are a metaphor for this collection of photographs featuring over sixty artists.
The project has also become a flamenco anthology, which will soon be released as an album of portraits featured in the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraiture led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" series ("SportARTproject").
Although the Flamenco people's concept differs slightly, the photographer adds: "I love taking pictures of people, getting to know them, and entering their lives for a longer or shorter time.
In my opinion, the most difficult art form in photography is portraiture.
You meet people, you meet people, you meet people you don't even know, or you just take a few minutes to take a picture.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my dreams come true.
The exhibition, which is a selection of contemporary flamenco portraits, entitled Flamenco-people, can be viewed at the El Fotómata Gallery, at number 20 of the calle de la Mata, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, until 16 October.
