Blood is safe again.
Hema-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and President-in-Office Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood donors in the world today.
Most importantly, he has regained the trust that was severely shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Service became infected with the acquired immune deficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the tragedy and the general upheaval, the Government of Canada launched an official investigation in February 1994 led by Judge Horace Krever to shed light on the circumstances leading to the tragedy and to make proposals to avoid similar incidents in the future.
While Judge Krever was delayed in submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committees to design a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has completed this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood services were established in Canada: one for Héma-Québec, serving Quebec, and the other for the Canadian Blood Service Company, which provides all other provinces and territories.
"When Héma-Québec began operating in 1998, only 38 percent of people had confidence in Québec's blood supply system", recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the years that followed, however, we were able to regain the trust of people by improving blood products and by working in the field". Décary proudly reports that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94 percent of Quebecers considered Hema-Québec to be reliable.
However, Dr. Decary remembers that "confidence is a very fragile thing".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
During this time, a number of cases of new strains of the disease, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were detected in Europe, the doctor, who has led the company since its founding in 1998, says.
"We had no idea if this disease was transmitted through blood.
So we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which is that if we are unsure of this and there is a risk of serious illness, we should take exclusionary measures.
So in April 1999, we refused blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was unquestionably established that the disease was also transmitted through blood.
This case convinced us that the precautionary principle made sense".
In 1999, a technique was introduced that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of HIV, the nucleic acid test (NAT), which can detect the virus directly in the blood of blood donors, rather than the antibodies to the virus that previously used tests were based on.
Using the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period from infection to detection of the virus in the blood using our technical tools, explains the expert.
This period could be shortened to less than a week.
This significantly reduced the risk of blood donors unknowingly contaminating the bloodstream and preventing it from being detected.
These advances have greatly reduced the risk of AIDS spreading through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million a person.
"In other words, we should be allocating 12 million blood products while someone is infected with HIV.
Since HEMA-Québec distributes 400 to 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to become infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that anyone today can readily accept or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health", says the head of the Hema-Québec.
"The challenge for the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen will enter the system.
It was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is introduced into the bloodstream through insect bites.
We must therefore be constantly on the loose", continued Dr. Décary, and stressed that in addition to the stocks of pesticides, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent stocks.
"As the population ages, so do the demands.
As cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or blood platelets to be replaced.
The ageing population also affects the blood donor population, with the number of people eligible to donate blood in the network representing only 3% of the population of Quebec.
However, any healthy person who is at least 18 years old and who meets the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of the respondents refuse blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is rampant are not eligible for blood transfusions for a year.
"We have enough reserves with that 3 percent to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's rare to run out of supplies.
But we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the people who are present get older because after a while they can no longer give blood.
But it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but even more difficult to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today's rushed world, a person has barely an hour to go and donate blood". - Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues such as bone grafts, heart valves, eye tissue and skin tissue, which are almost exclusively used for severely burned persons.
These tissues are analysed, transformed and frozen and then placed at Héma-Québec, which also manages Québec's only public stem cell bank.
Now, only medical waste can be used to produce blood that is rich in stem cells and can treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the first blood sample of the baby's blood a few weeks ago, and we plan to take more than a thousand new samples each year.
By the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering these for organ transplants", explained Dr. Décary, who said that the cord blood transfusion program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are saddened that they cannot afford this", - indeed, because Héma-Québec cannot afford to make this complex and expensive program available in every hospital in Québec.
