The Northern Purposes of Charest
The governor does not rule out that the election will begin this year
Just after the Liberal Party meeting, Jean Charest travelled to Jean-Talon, Quebec, yesterday, where the new health minister, Yves Bolduc (left), is seeking victory in the midterm elections to be held today.
"Straightening our last great northern border": this ambitious long-term goal was set by Jean Charès at the Liberal Party meeting in Levis, Quebec yesterday.
During his performance, behind his back, he was projected a film similar to "Moulin à images".
The three giant launchers were followed by impressive footage: damages for hydroelectric power plants, mining, Quebec on Google Maps, maps...
Such spectacular devices are used during election periods.
The Prime Minister, however, refused to guarantee at the press conference that the election would not start this autumn, although he added that his timetable was very tight.
The 'Northern Plan' is the fourth pillar of the Prime Minister's 'vision' for the future of Quebec, embodied in a 'new economic zone', which includes a labour agreement with France, a Canada-Europe agreement and several agreements with Ontario.
Recently, the opening of the North (i.e. the northern region starting at 49°N) has been a frequent theme in the Prime Minister's speeches, but he has never given a lecture on this topic.
However, the Head of State only insisted on explaining why he considers the North to be "a treasure trove of immense potential", but did not mention the time factor, the amount of investment or the precise order of importance for future projects.
It highlighted only a few development opportunities, notably in the water power sector, the forestry sector and in particular in the mining sector, which is further stimulated by the growth of the developing countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
"Nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds" are found in the north, Charest wrote.
This territory, which is "twice the size of France", "is our territory, the territory of Quebec.
It is not only in us, it is in us", the head of state repeated, stressing that he wants to create a national founding myth.
He stressed that Quebec's development was largely determined by its relationship with the North: the gold rush in Abitibi, the Quebec design work, James Bay...
"This is ours, our future!" he added, after taking a stage break and gazing at the giant map behind his back.
The north, which covers 70% of the territory of Quebec, includes part of Labrador, which Quebec has always demanded of itself, the Prime Minister told a press conference.
"This is our historic resolution, which has been confirmed by all governments.
There is a line on which there has been no agreement for a long time and if the opportunity arises I will reaffirm the same resolution on behalf of the government.'
On the other hand, "in the face of climate change, we must rethink our view of the North", the Prime Minister said, referring to the Northwest Passage, which opens every year as the polar ice melts.
The Prime Minister believes that in this new geopolitical environment, the occupation of the territory is an important task.
What about the natives of the area, the Indians and the Eskimos?
The Prime Minister stated that the Government of Quebec paid special attention to them and that the plan would bring many benefits, especially to young people.
Two ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (the latter was a delegate of the Parti Québécois) have already started the consultation with about thirty local communities.
It was also launched by an inter-ministerial committee headed by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Minister for Transport and Natural Resources) also plays an important role.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a large-scale meeting, "not necessarily a summit" where "they create a common vision".
The development of the North would, by the way, be in line with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be coordinated, systematic and environmentally friendly", the Prime Minister promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as being in line with the ideas of the liberal prime minister who preceded him.
"Like the liberals of the past, we think differently: our goal is to create new opportunities for growth and development through challenges".
This was, by the way, one of the recurring themes of the weekend that began with a large cocktail party on Friday to celebrate the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's election as president.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes the conversion of the Beauharnois power station into the Adélard-Godbout canal.
"Our Party's politicians, including Godbout, founder of Hydro-Québec, Lesage, who led the quiet revolution and the nationwide distribution of hydroelectric power plants, and Bourassa, known as the father of James Bay, all knew how to shape the future", said Jean Charest.
At the press conference, he quoted another true, conservative work, Prime Minister John Diefenbaker's "Roads to the North" program from 1957 to 1963.
In connection with the Eastmain1a-Ruper dam project, Chairman Charest stressed that the commissioning was planned for 2012.
"This should stay between us, but I plan to be there", he told his followers, and his statement was greeted with a loud applause.
The prime minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out a vote this fall, which the law allows.
However, he stressed that the calendar is now full, having taken on duties at the Federal Council meeting in China and the Quebec-New York summit.
The party's weekend meeting proved to be an excellent platform for the Liberal president to articulate nationalist resolutions, which were passed almost without thinking.
I also want Quebec to appoint members of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Council, and those members have the right to veto decisions made in Quebec.
The opposition, however, has been skeptical of the main points of the Northern Plan.
The leader of Parti Québécois, Paulina Marois, has re-examined the development policy in northern Quebec that was introduced by the Landry government in 2001.
Marois said the liberal government that came to power in 2003 had refused to apply this policy.
If they had not done so, "we would have gone much further today", Mrs Marois thought, in agreement with Françoise Mercure, who was launched as a candidate in the Jean-Talon vote to be held today.
The ADQ opposition party supports the government's acceptance of the Northern Plan.
"But we wish it wasn't just a game", noted Sébastien Proulx, the party leader who replaced Mario Dumont, who is returning from prison today.
