Opinion - The Orwellian speech by Barrick Gold
A letter was published in the September 17 issue of Le Devoir from Patrick J. Garver, vice president and general manager of the Barrick Gold mine in Canada.
Following Orwell's impeachment, Garver claims that the world's largest gold producer has filed a $6 million libel suit against three authors and a small-scale publisher to launch a so-called "public debate".
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decisions - especially in libel cases - are based on the law rather than on justice.
No wonder Garver listened deeply to this fundamental difference.
Is it really the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate is to destroy anyone who has a contrary view?
Regardless of the outcome of the case, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada must spend significant sums of money on defence and combat in an uneven struggle where the mining industry is supported by an army of lawyers with almost inexhaustible resources.
In such unequal combat, however, tactics are often employed to destroy the defendant and to make a friendly settlement, not only silencing the opponents but even intimidating those who would try to re-examine the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have been more about public opinion.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, this is different, in Canada the parties to the dispute do not usually slap each other but express their views.
So the mine would have just opened its books and files and prepared for a real debate in the press, the media, the publications, paying independent research groups to shed light on the issue.
But it seems Barrick Gold is not trusting the public and is moving to dismiss petitions and letters written to protect the authors of Noir Canada.
Mr. Garver, could you please explain how to initiate a "public" debate while at the same time ignoring this public opinion?
In the Vice President's mind, the word probably refers to only lawyers who are paid by bus, not the Canadian population as a whole.
In a democratic state, even those who despise others are allowed free speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are primarily supported by the public because they condemn the mining's harsh practices.
The public is willing to hear Barrick and make a judgment, but it would do so on the basis of civilized arguments rather than a lawsuit intended to silence many. (In a recent letter to the authors of Noir Canada, Barrick Gold has, by the way, called for the use of the term "public debate".)
In addition to Garver's surreal overtones, Barrick Gold's process is an open attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, the cornerstones of every democratic society.
In the course of the proceedings, he denies the right to quote credible sources, to debate anything about the facts and their interpretations that underlie the intellectual activities.
If in a country like Canada, you can only study and discuss issues that are not pleasing to the rich corporations of today's world under the weight of legal proceedings, who will have the courage to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wants an open and transparent debate, it could do so according to the scientific standards that the authors of Noir Canada apply.
You have a right to answer.
We have long been able to handle debates, differences and conflicts in our academic circles.
Barrick Gold's reckless course of action shows that contrary to what he claims, there is no willingness to openly debate.
This is a loss to both the university world and the Canadian Institute of Public Disputes, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit legal proceedings against such abuse.
Wall Street rescue - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the Republican and Democratic leaders of Congress finally agreed yesterday on an economic bailout, the largest such plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months still needs to be approved by both houses of Congress.
The main points of the plan are: more effective monitoring of implementation by representatives; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the planned public funds; new provisions to keep the number of houses occupied due to default; the right to access the salaries of the managers of the companies that received the aid.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Nancy Pelosi, Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives, and Judd Gregg, a Republican delegate to the hearing yesterday, announced the good news minutes before midnight after the two-day marathon hearing ended.
"We have made great progress toward a solution that will work effectively in the markets", said Henry Paulson, a spokesman for the Bush administration.
"We did everything to save the real economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"The most important aspect is that if we don't do this, there will be a huge amount of shock, chaos and chaos in the everyday lives of Americans", said Republican Rep. Judd Gregg.
The trial has been accelerated over the past few hours, fearing that another failure would have a detrimental effect on investors' mood.
The deal was given a deadline until the stock market opened this morning.
Two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late appeared willing to agree, but they expressed their displeasure that the situation had escalated to the final.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the extension of the agreement to provisions such as keeping house ownership or paying the heads of state-aided companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps for the irresponsibility of others, it is not a very pleasant thing.
But these steps are necessary", he noted on an American television show.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, he said, "I'd like to know the details, but I hope so".
"What I have read in great detail shows that this is something we all have to digest and move on.
The possibility of doing nothing is simply unacceptable", he said.
The $700 billion plan was to use taxpayer money to buy the dubious claims of American financial institutions, risky, unsold assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the housing bubble, which led to the collapse of risky mortgages, then spread to other credit-based (commercial) securities, and finally to the freezing of liquid assets and the collapse of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft of the agreement was defeated by a group of Republican lawmakers last week.
It seems we've been able to get out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed that certain "toxic" assets of troubled companies should be insured by the government rather than bought.
To satisfy all members of Congress, the plan included a provision that if the government had to bear losses under the program for five years, it could levy new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion installment would be paid first; an additional $100 billion could follow if the president deems it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion would have to be approved by Congress by a vote of no confidence.
In exchange for the help, Washington will get a stake in the subsidiaries, which will give him a dividend on the profits, and which he can sell after the crisis subsides.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to delay the foreclosure of the mortgage loans covered by the plan and to set the maximum amount of wages and final payments to the managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The plan makers want the bill to be approved by the House of Representatives today and the Senate Wednesday.
Despite their efforts, however, they are still unsure whether the plan will be approved.
Because yesterday, there were repeated statements against the plan from both the Republicans and Democrats.
"It is clear that Washington will not hear your voice", said House Finance Committee member Scott Garrett, a Republican.
"Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is none that would benefit taxpayers".
Brad Sherman, the Democratic congressman who leads a small group called the "sceptical faction", presents things differently, but he comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred leading economists, including three Nobel Prize-winning scientists, have written to us asking Congress not to rush and to consider carefully which path to take", Sherman said yesterday.
