The psychology of over-crowding: Why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neuroeconomic basis for this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been uncovered by researchers at New York University, neurologists and economists.
According to their study in the journal Science, people do not want to lose out in a type of competition, such as eBay auctions, and they are willing to pay too high a price.
The research attempted to map the neural system of this "play" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers took part in a lottery, the other group participated in a game auction, while the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) examined the active brain areas of the subjects.
Both games allowed participants to earn money, but in the auction game, where the other party's over-engagement was a key element, a sub-brain complex called the striatum became active when the game was lost.
This area of the brain, among other functions, plays a role in the "rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, the researchers believe that the price shock can be explained by the avoidance of the intense reaction of striatum.
To support their theory, the members of the research group, economists, also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this case, three groups bid against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they won the game, they would receive another $15 in prize money.
The third group received $15 just before the auction, but the group members lost that money in the event of a losing auction.
The only difference between the two groups was that the emphasis was on winning for one group and losing for the other.
However, proving the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the "loss" team were willing to bet higher than the control and the "power" group.
"These results cannot be inferred from any previous economic theory.
They have thus far explained the phenomena of auctioning only by the joy of winning and by avoiding risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, and now we have a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, a professor in the economics department at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and chronic liver disease is listed as the leading cause of death in Hungary.
The number of people infected with hepatitis at home can be in the hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand are treated, because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective name for infectious liver infections caused by various viruses.
They have many similarities, characterized by inflammation and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms, depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the feeding ducts (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (feces, bladder, saliva).
Travelers should be protected against A and B viruses, and there is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after eating infected food, generally accompanied by poor mood, weakness, stomach complaints, nausea.
Afterward, yellowing appears on the skin and whites of the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and the healing process can take two to three weeks.
Worldwide, one million people die each year of the more serious form of the disease, liver and liver disease caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that only one in ten infected people is estimated to receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver failure, liver cancer.
Most infected people are unaware of their disease because the pathogen secretly destroys liver cells, often not showing symptoms until 20 to 30 years later.
So it's very important to have early prevention, regular screening.
There were three groups with far higher than average incidence: people who had had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
There are currently 200 million people worldwide infected with chronic hepatitis C virus.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory tests, it is advisable to consult a doctor if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
If the disease is detected in time, it can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, eliminating infectiousness and preventing cancer.
World Hepatitis Day, which was first celebrated in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world, is celebrated on September 30.
It aims to draw attention to the chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection.
Does anyone who believes in God feel any less pain?
A recent study has shown that religious faith acts as a kind of pain reliever that could have eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment to investigate how belief in God influences people's perceptions of pain, reports The Telegraph.
