The flight of the dongos is imitated by the intelligent car
What better way to develop collision avoidance technologies than to mimic obstacle detectors in the natural world?
Like the bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the dongos gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C-type, bio-modulated robotic control system, a robotic minivan equipped with bee traits, with the ultimate goal of helping to develop a system that avoids all collisions.
During flight, each bee develops its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety coat", explained Kazuhhiro Doi, brand manager of technology PR and R&D at the exhibition.
It is important for the complex eye of the bee, which can see in more than 300 degrees in all directions.
To simulate the complex function of the eye, engineers developed the idea of a laser telescope.
This detects obstacles, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately transformed into a collision avoidance operation, within a distance of 2 metres from the BR23C at 180 degrees.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and the robot immediately changes direction by imitating the movements of the uterus, turning the wheels around to avoid the collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoiding maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If that wasn't the case, the car robot wouldn't be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
It shall react promptly and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of safety-belt cover, a layer within which collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to get rid of other bees.
This process should happen in a blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the difference cannot be upward, downward or transverse, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction of the reversal of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibility for bees to avoid other bees, only rotational motion and acceleration and slowing down were used as the option for the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy densities, meaning they have a longer lifetime than the lithium-ion variant.
Andoh says instinctive intelligence is the most important thing, not the ability to process data, but even less to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
You don't have to save them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so you're only using a few dozen kilobytes of memory all the time.
You don't need gigabytes or megabyte-sized memories.
This is the first step towards developing an immediate-output technology that Nissan estimates could be introduced into series production cars within 10 years.
Further application may be the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the vehicle to the destination by avoiding road obstacles.
