The Elite is in danger
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote on the $700 billion bailout package the White House put forward: a significant portion of Americans were more interested in, and still are, in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is supported by yesterday's New York Times report, which reports that the current crisis has created a rift within the Republican Party that is increasingly dividing between the traditional, restrained, East Coast attitude that supports federal institutions and business circles and the growing new anti-Washington and financial world trend in the central and southern states.
This trend was made clear in a critical way during the House vote referred to in the introduction.
But this is just one of the significant changes that the economic reorganization that is still taking place, not only in the United States, but in the entire Western world, and perhaps beyond, can foretell or predict.
It seems that the crisis in the United States and Europe is only accelerating the long-standing phenomena that are consolidating in this new environment and finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is the re-actualisation, the bringing back to public consciousness of a dual category of state sovereignty, in relation to a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is affecting banks and financial institutions that, while having close links with foreign countries, are attracting mainly and quite widely people and families living in one country, one state.
But this poses a direct political challenge to those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters.
So while the crisis seems global in an economic sense, it is almost exclusively national in a political sense.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially off the beaten track: a clear proof of this is the European Union, which, drawn between different interests and different national strategies, is unable to define a single political direction.
So everyone expects the individual national governments to intervene, to deliver a bailout, to revive and to introduce new rules, but above all to open up funds: because in a crisis situation only individual states have the economic resources, the financial resources that can make things right.
They have the means and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that are unlikely to be available to any other market or international organisation to such an extent.
At the same time, the new emphasis placed on nation-states by the crisis is fully consistent with the fact that economic growth in recent times has been increasingly attributed to a factor closely related to this element: territorial development.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we were entering the world of the abstract, the world of the more sophisticated technology, and that the global financial world was meant to rule the world, we suddenly had to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on abstract things like water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one half of the planet to another, but can be completely confined to a certain place, to a certain area.
So whoever controls the territory has a lot more cards than whoever was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
I'd like to turn to the second novelty, which is a kind of breaking point.
When you say territory, state, government, you're necessarily saying politics, in other words, leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis appears to produce two interrelated phenomena:
One is the objective recognition that we need authentic leadership, someone who can handle events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially the economic leaders, has brought complete loss of credibility, who have proved completely unfit and proved that there is still a long way to go.
The two together are even more profound and in some ways even more disturbing: the sense of loss of faith, impatience, incompetence and isolation that increasingly affects the entire leadership elite in Western countries.
So it seems that the belief that the social elite that has been at its peak to this day is over, is spreading to a wider population, and it is over before their actions, their experiences, their lifestyles, their culture, in the complex sense of the word, have been taken over, and this is increasingly alienating the social elite from the majority opinion.
In short, the demand for leadership is enveloped in a broad but strong delegitimization movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system, manifested in the unexpected "depression" of voters, or in the sudden changes in public sentiment in recent times, such as the rise to power of the Conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, or the U.S. Congressman's rebellion against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that with the traditional elite, its parties, programs, and even its media and its popular intellectual traditions, it is becoming less and less able to understand, and therefore less and less able to represent, what has been happening in the deepest layers of Western society for some time.
Yet, to speak of "the coming revolt of the masses" would be to be frankly exaggerated.
But it's not bad to walk with your eyes open.
