Fruit milk is forbidden.
You have to be careful with grapefruit, orange and tomatoes.
These high-vitamin drinks, especially popular in summer, when they are introduced into the body with certain life-saving medicines, alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing their effects, as the case may be, and can have serious health consequences.
The risks of using a combination of canned or fresh fruit juice and certain medicines were highlighted by David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, who reported at the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia that a glass of grapefruit, orange, or apple could reduce the absorption of certain life-saving medicines, preventing their beneficial effects and endangering the health of the patient.
Grapefruit juice was already on the defendants' bench when it was found to be able to increase the effects of some antibiotics, antihistamines, anxiety medications, heart rhythm regulators, and nerve drugs to levels considered toxic.
CONSUMMENTAL CONSUMMENT - Two years ago, the Italian Institute of Pharmaceuticals itself published the news in its official press release, warning doctors and patients to take seriously the risks associated with this concomitant use and to pay attention to what they drink when taking medicines such as Diazepam or Metadon.
GRAPEFRUIT - Researchers have found that oranges and apples contain substances that inhibit the effectiveness of medicines.
A long list of active substances that are inhibited by grapefruit and other fruit juices can be made.
Michele Carruba, professor of pharmacy at Milan State University, notes: "Discovery of this kind is usually immediately reported to various national and international pharmaceutical institutes, who, if necessary, make sure that the information in the product information is changed.
Therefore, it is always important to read the pharmacy information sheet and, if something is not understood, not to be influenced, but to clearly consult our doctor or pharmacist", emphasized the Ansa Institute's experts.
Paul Krugman was awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics
The American Paul Krugman was awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics for his analysis of business models and the territorial connections of economic activity.
55-year-old Neokynesian Krugman teaches at Princeton University and is a well-known publicist for The New York Times.
Krugman is one of the Bush administration's most vocal critics of economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 2001 terrorist attack, when Enron went bankrupt, Krugman predicted in a New York Times editorial that the latter event would have more fateful consequences for the history of the United States than the collapse of the Twin Towers.
This prediction has sparked much controversy, and has been repeatedly put on the economist's eye, but we now know that it was accurate.
"I am surprised and somewhat shocked by how quickly public interest has moved beyond the scandalous collapse of Enron or Worldcom", Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, member of the executive committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is a "very valuable economist" but "expresses his criticism of the Bush administration's excessive liberalism in a rather aggressive fashion".
Open Office, third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
OpenOffice.org 3.0 is an open source, personal productivity-enhancing application package that is now available as a free alternative to Microsoft Office, targeting a growing range of users from home to office, freelancers to government.
Supervised by SUN Microsystems and developed by volunteers for nearly a year, the new Open Office is bringing to the public with several new features: in addition to the greeting screen and the redesigned, less Spartan user interface, it also offers several significant innovations, such as compatibility with Apple's Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ISO-based Open Document Format (ODF) 1.2.
The focus has been on compatibility with Office 2007, allowing Open Office to open new Microsoft documents (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) with the extension.
There are some other module-specific features that are interesting, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations. This can be useful for sending files by email. Another feature supports importing PDFs into the graphics module by keeping the layout on the page.
Because we can also create "hybrid PDF" documents on this interface that combine the typical Adobe format with the table manager or text editor elements.
Sharing within applications has also undergone a number of improvements: the spreadsheet manager supports the sharing of workbooks but prevents overlapping each other's work.
Some companies are already working to make some of the features of OpenOffice available on the Internet (on the cloud, in the cloud), so the final version is likely to be released in the coming weeks.
The Italian version, which has been available in English since Friday, can be downloaded from the following address: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html
The software package is available for Linux in addition to the usual Windows and Mac OS operating systems.
We can download the installation CD on request, either at home or at work.
The most attractive feature for home application adoption is probably free software, but the Open Office suite is now trying to catch up with the business sector as it can also support a number of government and school projects.
There is also no lack of ideal education, consultancy and service services for small and medium-sized enterprises, which can open up new business opportunities.
Open Office consists of five core modules: Writer, a word-compatible text editor; Calc, a spreadsheet manager designed to replace Excel; Impress, a PowerPoint-like presentation; Dbase, the most well-known, similar to Access database manager; and finally Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, but considering that the new version is already at 3,600,000, that number is likely to be higher than expected.
