Students suffer from high rents, a room can cost up to 900 euros
The housing market for university students is not affected by the crisis.
According to the latest survey by the Union of Tenants, a student can pay up to 900 euros for a single room in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 euros in Naples and 600 euros in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached such staggering proportions that, because of the enormous costs to families, it has kept a wide range of students from learning", explains Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia study department. "The high demand from students in these cities has distorted the market to such an extent that a general price movement has begun against local residents".
In most cases, the offer of a property also involves a series of irregularities: unregistered contracts with no limitation on rents, with a rental attached.
Sunia considers that an exceptional measure would be necessary to maximise prices by reviewing the tax system.
The survey details that in Milan, near Brianza, a bed costs 450 euros; the average price of a single room ranges from 650 euros (Bande Nere) to 800 euros (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera) but can reach 900 euros (Vittoria).
In Florence, the average cost of a bed is 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where most students live near the university, a bed costs 250/280 euros for two beds and 370-500 euros for a single bed.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), the cost of a single bed is about 600 euros and a double bed 450 euros.
Prices are somewhat cheaper (€550 per single room) in the other university districts (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
In suburban areas, you can save a little: 300 euros for a bed and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and other similar districts.
In Naples, the cost of a bed is 300/450 euros, a room is 400-600 euros, and the highest in the area of Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, you have to pay 250/350 euros for a bed and at least 350 euros for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they represent a greater weight within the city budget.
Another disadvantage is that in cities such as Perugia, where students from outside the EU are also often looking for accommodation, the rental fees charged to foreign students are about 25 to 30% higher than those charged to Italian tenants.
Goodbye old Cinema Paradiso, the cities sacrificed the age of the old movie theaters
Traditional movie theaters are closing in on the Multiplex.
"A city without cinema, a blind city, is like a face without eyes".
The images by Giuseppe Tornatore show the effect of what is happening in the Italian cities and rural areas.
The suppression of cinema - the emergence of large, multi-screen cinema in the suburbs and the consequent displacement of single-screen cinema in the city centres - is a process that seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time carries all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When historical and memorable places disappear, "it's like a friend is leaving, a friend we've shared a journey with and many experiences with", says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which won an Academy Award and won the Grand Prix at the Cannes Film Festival twenty years ago, tells the story of a small-town movie theater, longing for a movie experience that may be lost forever.
The largest association of operators, Anec, has reported that 316 traditional cinemas have closed in the last five years, with the biggest losses in the cities being 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna, which lost 82 single-screen cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And that the multiplexers are responsible for their disappearance is no better proof than that Italy has the highest number of newly opened multi-screen theaters in these three regions: in the last five years, the number of theaters has increased by 195 in Lombardy, 81 in Tuscany and the same in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. "It is normal to build new facilities, but the survival of existing ones should also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not all stores are willing to switch to multiplexes.
Not to mention the unpaid financial funds to support operators: the outstanding debt of the State can be estimated at around EUR 10 million.
It's ethically and morally shameful that the government doesn't follow the laws.
It would take EUR 16-18 million a year to maintain the market.'
The case of Bologna is particularly noteworthy, the first Italian city to resolve the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec, in order to protect and promote the single cinema in the outer and inner cities.
The provisions would include tax incentives for operators and public benefits to promote accessibility: spectators can enter restricted areas and park in certain parking lots at a discounted rate.
"I like this initiative", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example, even with other measures.
But it's also clear that traditional movies, in order to be able to take on the battle against multiplex dominance, need to improve sound and image quality, because today's audiences are much more demanding.
The preservation of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheriya - where I spent my childhood and youth - gave me the spark that eventually led me to create Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, so when I go to the closed Rialto or the Quirinale on the Via Nazional to avoid seeing the posters blackened by dust, I turn my head.
