That energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones are coming.
An inexhaustible source of energy that covers 70 percent of the planet's surface, and it's only just been discovered by the big international energy companies.
Waves, tides, tides, all renewable energy sources that have been looked up by giants like Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on.
For a hundred years, they've been exploring the possibility of extracting energy from the ocean's motion, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, they explored it.
The idea of using marine energy was abandoned around 1980, when the price of crude oil fell, but today environmental demands and the renewed rise in crude oil prices give the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by ocean-going power plants.
That's twice what nuclear power plants are currently producing.
Besides, there'd be currents and currents.
The giants are in the air.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and in 2005 signed an agreement for a power plant to be built in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signing was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are voting for marine energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies and is considering collaborating with us", a spokesman for one of the U.S. oil giants' associates told the Wall Street Journal.
The cooperation in question concerns the approval of the US Energy Commission to launch the Alaska project for the recovery of marine energy.
This is not insignificant, especially considering that the United States is currently mining in Alaska, and even President Bush recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also developing offshore energy, and the investments so far, as far as the details are concerned, are evidence of growing interest.
The technology is still in development.
Experts say that this is still a very early technology, just because the energy from the sea does not dispel any doubts about environmental impact.
The existing facilities, like those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small and therefore do not pose a major problem for the ecosystem.
However, to produce energy on a larger scale, facilities with a greater environmental impact are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power uses a connected boiler system, for example.
The impulses generated by the waves and the booms moving up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the plungers and hoses placed inside them.
The pressure spins a turbine, which powers a generator.
Electricity is delivered to land by cables drawn under the sea.
There are currently four similar facilities in the planning stages, which are only awaiting federal approval, and some of the energy generated would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started producing power for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six underwater turbines located on the East River in New York.
When the water flows, it turns the turbine blades, and this rotational motion powers the generator.
Verdant said it had a long list of partners waiting for permits only for energy use.
Waves after waves.
The potential for the price movement is currently to be considered with a clear distinction.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, the price trend is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine, Alaska, and the other coastal states spent $7.5 million in 2008 on the energy of the tidal wave, which is projected to grow to $35 million in 2009.
